import java.util.PriorityQueue;

class KthLargest {
    private PriorityQueue<Integer> minHeap;
    private int k;
    public KthLargest(int k, int[] nums) {
        this.k = k;
        this.minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>(k);
     for (int num : nums) 
            add(num);
    }
    public int add(int val) {
        minHeap.offer(val);
        if (minHeap.size() > k) 
            minHeap.poll();
        return minHeap.peek();
    }
}


Time Complexity
Constructor (KthLargest): O(N log k)
We iterate through the initial array of N elements.
For each element, we call the add method.
Inside add, inserting into a heap of maximum size k takes O(log k) time.
Therefore, processing all initial elements takes O(N log k) time.
add(val) Method: O(log k)
Pushing the new element into the priority queue takes O(log k) time.
Popping the smallest element (if the heap size exceeds k) also takes O(log k) time.
Since these heap operations are bounded by the maximum size k, each add call runs in logarithmic time relative to k.

Space Complexity
Overall Space Complexity: O(k)
The Min-Heap is strictly constrained to hold at most k elements at any given moment.
Even if the incoming stream grows to millions of scores, the memory footprint remains constant at O(k) because we instantly discard elements that drop out of the top k threshold.

